<section xml:id="sec-double-integrals-over-general-regions">
  <title>Double integrals over general regions</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Handle irregular regions by extending the integrand to a surrounding rectangle.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Set up iterated integrals by describing the region with inequalities bounding one variable in terms of the other.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Reverse the order of integration to simplify difficult integrals.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Can use a <sq>bounding box</sq> approach to take double integrals over regions with more general regions.
        If <m>D</m> is a region over which <m>f</m> is defined, let <m>R</m> be a rectangle containing <m>D</m>, and let
        <me>
          F(x,y)=\begin{cases}f(x,y) \amp \text{if }(x,y)\in D\\ 0 \amp \text{if }(x,y)\in R\setminus D\end{cases}
        </me>
        Then <m>\DS\iint_{D} f(x,y)\dd{A}=\iint_{R} F(x,y)\dd{A}</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>D</m> is bounded below by <m>y=g(x)</m> and above by <m>y=h(x)</m>:
        <me>
          \iint_{D} f(x,y)\dd{A}=\int_{x=a}^{x=b}\int_{y=g(x)}^{y=h(x)}f(x,y)\dd{y}\dd{x}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>D</m> is bounded on the left by <m>x=g(y)</m> and the right by <m>x=h(y)</m>:
        <me>
          \iint_{D} f(x,y)\dd{A}=\int_{y=c}^{y=d}\int_{x=g(y)}^{x=h(y)}f(x,y)\dd{x}\dd{y}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Changing order of integration:
        <me>
          \int_{x=0}^{x=1}\int_{y=x}^{y=1}\sin(y^{2})\dd{y}\dd{x}=\int_{y=0}^{y=1}\int_{x=0}^{x=y}\sin(y^{2})\dd{x}\dd{y}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
